Pilot Test

2023-07-25

Load pacakges

library(readr)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggthemes)

Prepare data

# load data
df <- read_csv("df.csv")

# define data type
df %>%
  mutate(
    user_id = as.factor(user_id),
    tweet_id = as.factor(tweet_id),
    friend_id = as.factor(account_id)
  ) %>%
  dplyr::select(-account_id) -> df

# define x-axis: number of tweets collected during one week
df %>%
  group_by(user_id) %>%
  count(tweet_id) %>%
  mutate(
    x = cumsum(n)
  ) %>%
  dplyr::select(
    user_id, tweet_id, x
  ) -> df_for_x

df %>%
  inner_join(df_for_x, by=c("user_id", "tweet_id")) -> df 

# define y-axis: count how many distinct accounts are in the tweets (numerator) 
# make a fraction for y-axis (user_friends_count as denominator)

df %>% 
  arrange(user_id,desc(-x)) %>%
  group_by(user_id) %>%
  mutate(
    numerator =   cumsum(!duplicated(friend_id)),
    y = numerator / user_friends_count
  ) -> df2 
# df2 is the final data for drawing plots

Plot 1.

  • x-axis: number of tweets collected
  • y-axis: % of distinct accounts in tweets (= Total number of distinct accounts that have appeared in tweets collected so far / Total number of friends of an user)
# plot 1. 
df2 %>%
  group_by(user_id) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=x, y=y, col=user_id)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  theme_few() + 
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  xlab("Number of Tweets Collected") +
  ylab("Fraction of Distinct Accounts Appearing in Tweets (%)") +
  scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 10)

Plot 2.

Taking log to x-axis (rescale due to outliers)?

df2 %>%
  group_by(user_id) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=x, y=y, col=user_id)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  theme_few() + 
  theme(legend.position="none") +

  xlab("(Log) Number of Tweets Collected")

Plot 3. Grid by User

In the data frame (df2), there are 60 unique users.

df2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=x, y=y, col=user_id)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  theme_few() + 
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  xlab("Number of Tweets Collected") +
  ylab("Fraction of Distinct Accounts Appearing in Tweets (%)") +
  scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 10) +
  facet_wrap(~user_id, ncol = 6, scales="fixed")

Plot 4 & Plot 5

Lets redraw the plot but by separating the samples into smaller chunks. I also allow scales of the x-axis to vary for each user.

df2 %>% 
  mutate(numeric_user_id = as.integer(user_id)) %>%
  filter(numeric_user_id < 31) %>% # from 1~30
  ggplot(aes(x=x, y=y, col=user_id)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  theme_few() + 
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  xlab("Number of Tweets Collected") +
  ylab("Fraction of Distinct Accounts Appearing in Tweets (%)") +
  scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 5) +
  facet_wrap(~user_id, nrow=10, ncol=6, scales="free_x") +
  ggtitle("First 30 users")

df2 %>% 
  mutate(numeric_user_id = as.integer(user_id)) %>%
  filter(numeric_user_id > 30) %>% # from 31~60
  ggplot(aes(x=x, y=y, col=user_id)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  theme_few() + 
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  xlab("Number of Tweets Collected") +
  ylab("Fraction of Distinct Accounts Appearing in Tweets (%)") +
  scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 5) +
  facet_wrap(~user_id, nrow=10, ncol=6, scales="free_x") +
  ggtitle("Second 30 users")

Plot 6: Aggregate plot

  • Take the mean of y-axis by each point of x
  • Hence, the y-axis indicates the mean fraction of distinct accounts that users see for each (cumulative) number of tweets collected.
# aggregate plot: mean of y-axis by each point of x 
df2 %>%
  group_by(x) %>%
  summarize(y = mean(y)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) + 
  geom_smooth(color='darkcyan', linewidth=0.5) + 
  theme_few() + 
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  xlab("Number of Tweets Collected") +
  ylab("Mean of distinct accounts / # of friends (%)") +
  scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 10) 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'
